nt a messenger to the invader with a polite announcement that they were henceforth unable to support him; because, you see, ‘the ling’ “—that is, the heather of the plain across which the turncoat army was to pass to join with the foreign forces—” ‘had entwined the stirrups and shins of treachery, thus preventing further advance,’ which apparently is to be taken literally, and not interpreted in the spirit of those stale allegories on which schoolboys are nourished. Then again—